# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: african-methodist-episcopal-church
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/14th-district-of-the-african-methodist-episcopal-church] The American-founded African Methodist Episcopal Church's 14th district covers Benin, Côte d'Ivoire, Ghana, Liberia, Nigeria, Sierra Leone and Togo.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/14th-district-of-the-african-methodist-episcopal-church] It has a significant presence in Nigeria.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/14th-district-of-the-african-methodist-episcopal-church] The bishop of the 14th district is since July 2016 Bishop E.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/14th-district-of-the-african-methodist-episcopal-church] Earl McCloud, Jr. from the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/14th-district-of-the-african-methodist-episcopal-church] In Nigeria, the rise of Boko Haram has displaced churches of the AME Zion denomination and threatened their viability.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/1949-in-radio] The year 1949 saw a number of significant events in radio broadcasting history.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The **54th Massachusetts Infantry Regiment** is an infantry regiment that saw extensive service in the Union Army during the American Civil War.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The unit was the second African-American regiment, following the 1st Kansas Colored Volunteer Infantry Regiment, organized in the Northern states during the Civil War.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Authorized by the Emancipation Proclamation, the regiment consisted of African-American enlisted men commanded by white officers.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 54th Massachusetts was a major force in the pioneering of African-American civil war regiments, with 150 all-black regiments being raised after the raising of the 54th Massachusetts.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The unit began recruiting in February 1863 and trained at Camp Meigs on the outskirts of Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Prominent abolitionists were active in recruitment efforts, including Frederick Douglass, whose two sons were among the first to enlist.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Massachusetts Governor John Albion Andrew, who had long pressured the U.S.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Department of War to begin recruiting African-Americans, placed a high priority on the formation of the 54th Massachusetts.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Andrew appointed Robert Gould Shaw, the son of Boston abolitionists, to command the regiment as Colonel.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The free black community in Boston was also instrumental in recruiting efforts, utilizing networks reaching beyond Massachusetts and even into the Southern states to attract soldiers and fill out the ranks.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After it departed from Massachusetts on May 28, 1863, the 54th Massachusetts was shipped to Beaufort, South Carolina, and became part of the X Corps commanded by Major General David Hunter.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] During its service with the X Corps, the 54th Massachusetts took part in operations against Charleston, South Carolina, including the Battle of Grimball's Landing on July 16, 1863, and the more famous Second Battle of Fort Wagner on July 18, 1863.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] During the latter engagement, the 54th Massachusetts, with other Union regiments, executed a frontal assault against Fort Wagner and suffered casualties of 20 killed, 125 wounded, and 102 missing (primarily presumed dead)—roughly 40 percent of the unit's numbers at that time.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Shaw was killed on the parapet of Fort Wagner.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In 1864, as part of the Union Army's Department of Florida, the 54th Massachusetts took part in the Battle of Olustee.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The service of the 54th Massachusetts, particularly their charge at Fort Wagner, soon became one of the most famous episodes of the war, interpreted through artwork, poetry, and song.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] More recently, the 54th Massachusetts gained prominence in popular culture through the 1989 Oscar-winning film *Glory*.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] General recruitment of African Americans for service in the Union Army was authorized by the Emancipation Proclamation issued by President Lincoln on January 1, 1863.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Stanton accordingly instructed the Governor of Massachusetts, John A.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Andrew, to begin raising regiments including "persons of African descent" on January 26, 1863.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Andrew selected Robert Gould Shaw to be the regiment's colonel and Norwood Penrose "Pen" Hallowell to be its lieutenant colonel.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Like many officers of regiments of African-American troops, both Robert Gould Shaw and Hallowell, captains at the time, were promoted several grades.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The rest of the officers were evaluated by Shaw and Hallowell: these officers included Luis Emilio, and Garth Wilkinson "Wilkie" James, brother of Henry James and William James.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Many of these officers were of abolitionist families, and Governor Andrew himself chose several.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Norwood Hallowell was joined by his younger brother Edward Needles Hallowell, who commanded the 54th as a full colonel for the rest of the war after Shaw's death.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Twenty-four of the 29 officers was veterans, but only six had been previously commissioned.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The soldiers were recruited by black abolitionists like Frederick Douglass and Major Martin Robison Delany, M.D., and white abolitionists, including Shaw's parents.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Appleton, the first white man commissioned in the regiment, posted a notice in the *Boston Journal*.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Pierce spoke at a Joy Street Church recruiting rally, encouraging free blacks to enlist.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] About 100 people were actively involved in recruitment, including those from Joy Street Church and a group of individuals appointed by Governor Andrew to enlist black men for the 54th.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Stephens, African-American military correspondent to the *Weekly Anglo-African* who recruited over 200 men in Philadelphia and would go on to serve as a First Sergeant in the 54th.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 54th trained at Camp Meigs in Readville near Boston.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] While there, they received considerable moral support from abolitionists in Massachusetts, including Ralph Waldo Emerson.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Material support included warm clothing items, battle flags, and $500 contributed for the equipping and training of a regimental band.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] As it became evident that many more recruits were coming forward than were needed, the medical exam for the 54th was described as "rigid and thorough" by the Massachusetts Surgeon-General.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] This resulted in what he described as "a more robust, strong and healthy set of men were never mustered into the service of the United States." Despite this, as was common in the Civil War, a few men died of disease before the 54th departed from Camp Meigs.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] By most accounts, the 54th left Boston with very high morale.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] This was despite the fact that Jefferson Davis's proclamation of December 23, 1862, effectively put both African-American enlisted men and white officers under a death sentence if captured on the grounds that they were inciting servile insurrection.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After muster into federal service on May 13, 1863, the 54th left Boston with fanfare on May 28, and arrived to more celebrations in Beaufort, South Carolina.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] They were greeted by local blacks and by Northern abolitionists, some of whom had deployed from Boston a year earlier as missionaries to the Port Royal Experiment.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In Beaufort, they joined with the 2nd South Carolina Volunteers, a unit of South Carolina freedmen led by James Montgomery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After the 2nd Volunteers' successful Raid at Combahee Ferry, Montgomery led both units in a raid on the town of Darien, Georgia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The population had fled, and Montgomery ordered the soldiers to loot and burn the empty town.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Shaw objected to this activity and complained over Montgomery's head that burning and looting were not suitable activities for his model regiment.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment's first engagement took place during the Battle of Grimball's Landing on James Island, just outside of Charleston, South Carolina, on July 16, 1863.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The Union attack on James Island was intended to draw Confederate troops away from Fort Wagner in anticipation of an upcoming Union assault on the fort.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] During the Battle of Grimball's Landing, the 54th Massachusetts stopped a Confederate advance, taking 45 casualties in the process.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In an account of the engagement, which was later published, First Sergeant Robert John Simmons of the 54th Massachusetts (a British Army veteran from Bermuda) described a "desperate battle" in which about 250 pickets of the regiment were attacked by about 900 Confederates.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] He estimated that a reserve of 3,000 men supported the Confederates in their front.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After the engagement, their division commander, Brig.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Terry, complimented "steadiness and soldierly conduct" of 54th Massachusetts by courier to Col.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Shaw and in his official report of the action.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] This recognition raised the morale of the regiment.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The regiment gained widespread acclaim on July 18, 1863, when it spearheaded an assault on Fort Wagner, a key position overlooking the water approach to Charleston Harbor.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 54th Massachusetts had only recently returned from James Island after a difficult withdrawal during which they spent two days without food.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] They returned to the main Union force late on the afternoon of July 18 and the tired and hungry men were immediately placed in the vanguard of the assault force of 4,000 men.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The assault was launched at 7:45 pm along a narrow spit of land.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The distance to the Confederate line was some 1,600 yards (4,800 ft), and the spit and treacherous marshland's narrow confines disorganized the attackers.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The approach required them to pass beyond some of the Confederate fortifications before turning to make their assault.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The men crossed a water-filled ditch and took the fort's outer wall.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Because of the strength of the defending force, the position could only be held for an hour before the two Union brigades were withdrawn at around 9:00 pm.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 54th Massachusetts numbered 600 men at the time of the assault.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Of these, 270 were killed, wounded, or captured during the engagement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Shaw was killed, along with 29 of his men; 24 more later died of wounds, 15 were captured, 52 were missing in action and never accounted for, and 149 were wounded.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] These casualties represented the highest in the history of the regiment during a single engagement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Two company commanders were killed during the attack.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Decades later, Sergeant William Harvey Carney was awarded the Medal of Honor for grabbing the U.S. flag as the flag bearer fell, carrying the flag to the enemy ramparts and back, and saying "Boys, the old flag never touched the ground!" which would be turned into a song in his honor in 1900.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] While other African Americans had since been granted the award by the time it was presented to Carney, Carney's is the earliest action for which the Medal of Honor was awarded to an African American.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After the battle of Fort Wagner many officers had been killed leading to vacancies in leadership.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Non-commissioned officers exercised de-facto control of their companies due to these vacancies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Rather than promote black soldiers to these open roles, inexperienced whites were brought from other regiments to lead the 54th Massachusetts, many of whom lacked the same anti-slavery convictions as the previous white officers.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Under the command of now-Colonel Edward Hallowell, the 54th fought a rear-guard action covering the Union retreat to Jacksonville, Florida, after their defeat at the Battle of Olustee.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] During the retreat they, along with the 35th United States Colored Troops, were able to repulse the Confederate advance and secure the Union withdrawal to Jacksonville.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 54th Massachusetts was sent up from the reserves into the fight as the seventh New Hampshire and Eighth Colored Troops broke into retreat.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] It was here that their delaying action covered the withdrawal of the Union forces, with the 54th Massachusetts expending over 20,000 rounds of ammunition.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After the Battle there was a large number of wounded soldiers and abandoned equipment from the 54th Massachusetts, as well as the Federal Cavalry, and part of the 7th Connecticut.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Fortunately for the Union forces, the Confederate pursuit of their massive retreat was poorly executed, and the Union soldiers were able to retreat to safety.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] While retreating, the unit was suddenly ordered to counter-march back to Ten Mile station.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The locomotive of a train carrying wounded Union soldiers had broken down, and the wounded were in danger of capture.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] When the 54th arrived, the men attached ropes to the engine and cars and manually pulled the train approximately three miles (4.8 km) to Camp Finegan, where horses were secured to help pull the train.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After that, the train was pulled by both men and horses to Jacksonville for a total distance of ten miles (16 km).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] It took 42 hours to pull the train that distance.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The Union army successfully retreated to Jacksonville two days after the battle on February 22.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] By the end of the ordeal, from the arrival of the 54th Massachusetts to Olustee, the fighting of the battle, and then the retreat back to Jacksonville, the troops had marched roughly 120 miles in a span of four and a half days, causing exhaustion within the regiment.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] This defeat at Olustee, along with the Union retreat after the battle, was not without consequences; there were 1,861 total casualties for the Union: 203 deaths, 1,152 wounded, and 506 missing in action.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Of that total, 87 casualties came from the 54th Massachusetts during their rearguard action with three officers and 84 enlisted men either being killed, wounded or missing.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In contrast to the Confederate forces, this total was greatly imbalanced; with 946 casualties for the Confederates, a 5,400 strong force, roughly equal to what the Union had brought to the battle.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In the aftermath of the war, discrepancies appeared surrounding the battle of Olustee, which revolved around the involvement of the 7th Connecticut and the 54th Massachusetts.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Brevet Major General Joseph Hawley, commanding the second brigade of Seymour's army, containing the 7th Connecticut, 7th New Hampshire and Eighth United States Colored Troops, was frustrated by what he considered inaccuracy in newspaper reports.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] He stated, "The papers are so full of lies that I know that no true history of any event was ever or ever will be written".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Hawley wrote to Charles Dudley saying, "Don't publish the damned lie that anybody on foot but the 7th Conn. covered the entire retreat from Olustee.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The 'officer' who wrote the lie that the 54th Mass. and the 1st Nor.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] 'Saved the day' and 'covered the retreat' deserves to be shot.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Later in the Florida campaign, as part of an all-black brigade under Col.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Hartwell, the 54th Massachusetts unsuccessfully attacked entrenched Confederate militia at the November 1864 Battle of Honey Hill.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In mid-April 1865, they fought at the Battle of Boykin's Mill, a small affair in South Carolina that proved to be one of the last engagements of the war.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The enlisted men of the 54th were recruited on the promise of pay and allowances equal to their white counterparts.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] This was supposed to amount to subsistence and $13 a month.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Instead, they were informed upon arriving in South Carolina that the Department of the South would pay them only $7 per month ($10 with $3 withheld for clothing, while white soldiers did not pay for clothing at all.) Colonel Shaw and many others immediately began protesting the measure.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Joseph Barquet, another member of the regiment, also protested the quality of the food which the soldiers were given, which led to him being court-martialed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Although Massachusetts offered to make up the difference in pay, on principle, a regiment-wide boycott of the pay tables on paydays became the norm.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After Shaw's death at Fort Wagner, Colonel Edward Needles Hallowell took up the fight to get full pay for the troops.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Hooper took command of the regiment starting June 18, 1864.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] After nearly a month, Colonel Hallowell returned on July 16.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Refusing their reduced pay became a point of honor for the men of the 54th.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The Congressional bill, enacted on June 16, 1864, authorized equal and full pay to those enlisted troops who had been free men as of April 19, 1861.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Of course, not all the troops qualified.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Colonel Hallowell, a Quaker, rationalized that because he did not believe in slavery, he could have all the troops swear that they were free men on April 19, 1861.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Before being given their back pay, the entire regiment was administered what became known as "the Quaker oath".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Colonel Hallowell skillfully crafted the oath to say: "You do solemnly swear that you owed no man unrequited labor on or before the 19th day of April 1861.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Congress took action to pay the men of the 54th.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] A monument to Shaw and the 54th Massachusetts regiment, constructed 1884–1898 by Augustus Saint-Gaudens on the Boston Common, is part of the Boston Black Heritage Trail.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In 1897, at the unveiling of the monument in Boston, William James gave a memorial address.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] A plaster of this monument was displayed in the entryway to the U.S. paintings galleries at the Paris Universal Exposition of 1900.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] A patinated plaster copy from 1900 is currently displayed in the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Shaw and his Colored Regiment", the opening movement of *Three Places in New England*, is based both on the monument and the regiment.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Swails of the 54th Massachusetts regiment became the first African American to receive commission as an officer of a combat regiment of the regular Union army.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Colonel Shaw and his men feature prominently in Robert Lowell's Civil War centennial poem "For the Union Dead." It was originally titled "Colonel Shaw and the Massachusetts' 54th" and published in *Life Studies* (1959).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] In the poem, Lowell uses the Robert Gould Shaw memorial as a symbolic device to comment on broader societal change, including racism and segregation, as well as his more personal struggle to cope with a rapidly changing Boston.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Blight suggested "missed filmic opportunities" that might have been included the movie.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The unit was reactivated on November 21, 2008, to serve as the Massachusetts Army National Guard ceremonial unit to render military honors at funerals and state functions.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The new unit is known as the 54th Massachusetts Volunteer Regiment.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] 54th Mass Volunteer Infantry Company A is a living history and reenactment group based in Hyde Park, Massachusetts where the original regiment was formed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The company marches during key holidays, events and ceremonies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] When invited, they also stage information booths, provide talks to educate the public about the 54th and participate in historical reenactments along the east coast.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] The group is affiliated with the official Massachusetts National Guard 54th regiment and often do events together.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/54th-massachusetts-volunteer-infantry-regiment] Company A office is located at 55-59 Harvard Ave, in Hyde Park, and drill at historic Camp Meigs Playground.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] Church Review*** is the journal of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] Established in 1841 and revived in 1884, it is arguably the earliest published African-American journal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] It publishes articles on religion, politics, history, and world events.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] Church Magazine*, it was first published in September 1841 by the church's general book steward, Rev.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] It was intended to be a monthly publication, but appeared only sporadically and was discontinued after eight years due to lack of funds.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] At the 1884 General Conference, the name of the organization's publication was changed to *A.M.E.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] Benjamin Tucker Tanner was elected editor.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] He was succeeded by Levi Jenkins Coppin in 1888; Hightower Theodore Kealing in 1896; and Reverdy C.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] Early contributors to the journal included abolitionist Frederick Douglass, journalist Frances Ellen Watkins Harper, editor T.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] Thomas Fortune, Judge David Augustus Straker, educator William Sanders Scarborough, Senator Blanche Kelso Bruce, author Theophilus Gould Steward, attorney T.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-m-e-church-review] McCants Stewart, and bishops Daniel Alexander Payne, Henry McNeal Turner, and Jabez Pitt Campbell.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] The **African Union Methodist Protestant Church** (**AUMPC**), abbreviated as **A.U.M.P.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] It was chartered by Peter Spencer (1782–1843) in Wilmington, Delaware, in 1813 as the "Union Church of Africans", where it became known as the "African Union Church".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] The formation of the African Union Methodist Protestant Church is a part of the history of Methodism in the United States; in 1866, the First Colored Methodist Protestant Church merged with it.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] This was a Maryland offshoot of the A.M.E.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] Church, which was based in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] The Delaware-Maryland denomination renamed itself, combining names, as the *African Union First Colored Methodist Protestant Church and Connection*, usually called the A.U.M.P.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] In the 1860s, a schism resulted in some of the congregations forming the "Union American Methodist Episcopal Church" in 1865.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] The two denominations are now referred to collectively as the "Spencer Churches" (or, less often, the "Union Churches").
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] Although a decentralized Methodist Protestant church in its earlier years, the A.U.M.P.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] Church in the 1880s began to consider adopting an episcopal structure.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] In 1922 it consecrated its first bishop, Daniel J.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] But it was not until 1967 that the Church fully changed to an episcopal structure and consecrated its two leaders as bishops.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/a-u-m-p-church] Church has a total of about 40 congregations in the area of the mid-Atlantic and Upper South: the states of New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Maryland, Delaware, and the District of Columbia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The first country to fully outlaw slavery was France in 1315, though it was later used in its colonies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The first country to abolish and punish slavery for indigenous people was Spain with the New Laws in 1542.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Under the actions of Toyotomi Hideyoshi, chattel slavery was abolished across Japan since 1590, though other forms of forced labor were used during World War II.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The first and only country to self-liberate from slavery was a former French colony, Haiti, as a result of the Revolution of 1791–1804.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The British abolitionist movement began in the late 18th century, and the 1772 Somersett case established that slavery did not exist in English law.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1807, the slave trade was made illegal throughout the British Empire, though existing slaves in British colonies were not liberated until the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In the United States, Pennsylvania and Vermont were the first states to abolish slavery, Vermont in 1777 and Pennsylvania in 1780 (Vermont did not join the Union until 1791).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] By 1804, the rest of the northern states had abolished slavery, but it remained legal in southern states.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] By 1808, the United States outlawed the importation of slaves and in 1865 outlawed slavery except as a punishment.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In Eastern Europe, groups organized to abolish the enslavement of the Roma in Wallachia and Moldavia between 1843 and 1855, and to emancipate the serfs in Russia in 1861.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The United States would pass the 13th Amendment in December 1865 after having just fought a bloody Civil War, ending slavery "except as a punishment for crime".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1888, Brazil became the last country in the Americas to outlaw slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] As the Empire of Japan annexed Asian countries, from the late 19th century onwards, archaic institutions including slavery were abolished in those countries.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1948, slavery was declared illegal in the United Nations' Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] By this time, the Arab world was the only region in the world where institutional chattel slavery was still legal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Slavery in Saudi Arabia, slavery in Yemen and slavery in Dubai were abolished in 1962–1963, with slavery in Oman following in 1970.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Mauritania is the latest country to officially abolish slavery, with a presidential decree in 1981.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Today, child and adult slavery and forced labor are illegal in almost all countries, as well as being against international law, but human trafficking for labor and for sexual slavery continues to affect tens of millions of adults and children.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Balthild of Chelles, herself a former slave, queen consort of Neustria and Burgundy by marriage to Clovis II, became regent in 657 since the king, her son Chlothar III, was only five years old.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] At some unknown date during her rule, she abolished the trade of slaves, although not slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Moreover, her (and contemporaneous Saint Eligius') favorite charity was to buy and free slaves, especially children.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Slavery started to dwindle and would be superseded by serfdom.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1315, Louis X, king of France, published a decree proclaiming that "France signifies freedom" and that any slave setting foot on French soil should be freed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] This prompted subsequent governments to circumscribe slavery in the overseas colonies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Some cases of African slaves freed by setting foot on French soil were recorded such as the example of a Norman slave merchant who tried to sell slaves in Bordeaux in 1571.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] He was arrested and his slaves were freed according to a declaration of the Parlement of Guyenne which stated that slavery was intolerable in France, although it is a misconception that there were 'no slaves in France'; thousands of African slaves were present in France during the 18th century.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Born into slavery in Saint Domingue, Thomas-Alexandre Dumas became free when his father brought him to France in 1776.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] As in other New World colonies, the French relied on the Atlantic slave trade for labor for their sugar cane plantations in their Caribbean colonies; the French West Indies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In addition, French colonists in *Louisiane* in North America held slaves, particularly in the South around New Orleans, where they established sugarcane plantations.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Louis XIV's *Code Noir* regulated the slave trade and institution in the colonies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It included the right to marry, gather publicly or take Sundays off.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Although the *Code Noir* authorized and codified cruel corporal punishment against slaves under certain conditions, it forbade slave owners to torture them or to separate families.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It also demanded enslaved Africans receive instruction in the Catholic faith, implying that Africans were human beings endowed with a soul, a fact French law did not admit until then.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It resulted in a far higher percentage of Black people being free in 1830 (13.2% in Louisiana compared to 0.8% in Mississippi).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] They were on average exceptionally literate, with a significant number of them owning businesses, properties, and even slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Other free people of colour, such as Julien Raimond, spoke out against slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The *Code Noir* also forbade interracial marriages, but it was often ignored in French colonial society and the mulattoes became an intermediate caste between whites and blacks, while in the British colonies mulattoes and blacks were considered equal and discriminated against equally.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] During the Age of Enlightenment, many philosophers wrote pamphlets against slavery and its moral and economical justifications, including Montesquieu in *The Spirit of the Laws* (1748) and Denis Diderot in the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, Jacques Pierre Brissot founded the Society of the Friends of the Blacks (*Société des Amis des Noirs*) to work for the abolition of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] After the Revolution, on 4 April 1792, France granted free people of colour full citizenship.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The slave revolt, in the largest Caribbean French colony of Saint-Domingue in 1791, was the beginning of what became the Haitian Revolution led by formerly enslaved people like Georges Biassou, Toussaint L'Ouverture, and Jean-Jacques Dessalines.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion swept through the north of the colony, and with it came freedom to thousands of enslaved blacks, but also violence and death.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1793, French Civil Commissioners in St.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Domingue and abolitionists, Léger-Félicité Sonthonax and Étienne Polverel, issued the first emancipation proclamation of the modern world (Decree of 16 Pluviôse An II).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The Convention sent them to safeguard the allegiance of the population to revolutionary France.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The proclamation resulted in crucial military strategy as it gradually brought most of the black troops into the French fold and kept the colony under the French flag for most of the conflict.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The connection with France lasted until blacks and free people of colour formed L'armée indigène in 1802 to resist Napoleon's Expédition de Saint-Domingue.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Victory over the French in the decisive Battle of Vertières finally led to independence and the creation of present Haiti in 1804.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The convention, the first elected Assembly of the First Republic (1792–1804), on 4 February 1794, under the leadership of Maximilien Robespierre, abolished slavery in law in France and its colonies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Abbé Grégoire and the Society of the Friends of the Blacks were part of the abolitionist movement, which had laid important groundwork in building anti-slavery sentiment in the metropole.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The first article of the law stated that "Slavery was abolished" in the French colonies, while the second article stated that "slave-owners would be indemnified" with financial compensation for the value of their slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The French constitution passed in 1795 included in the declaration of the Rights of Man that slavery was abolished.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars, French slave-owners joined the counter-revolution en masse and, through the Whitehall Accord, they threatened to move the French Caribbean colonies to British control, as Great Britain still allowed slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Fearing secession from these islands, successfully lobbied by planters and concerned about revenues from the West Indies, and influenced by the slaveholder family of his wife, Napoleon Bonaparte decided to re-establish slavery after becoming First Consul.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] He promulgated the law of 20 May 1802 and sent military governors and troops to the colonies to impose it.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] On 10 May 1802, Colonel Delgrès launched a rebellion in Guadeloupe against Napoleon's representative, General Richepanse.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion was repressed, and slavery was re-established.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The news of the Law of 4 February 1794 that abolished slavery in France and its colonies and the revolution led by Colonel Delgrès sparked another wave of rebellion in Saint-Domingue.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] From 1802 Napoleon sent more than 20,000 troops to the island, two-thirds died, mostly from yellow fever.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Seeing the failure of the Saint-Domingue expedition, in 1803 Napoleon decided to sell the Louisiana Territory to the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The French governments initially refused to recognize Haïti.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It forced the nation to pay a substantial amount of reparations (which it could ill afford) for losses during the revolution and did not recognize its government until 1825.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] France was a signatory to the first multilateral treaty for the suppression of the slave trade, the Treaty for the Suppression of the African Slave Trade (1841), but the king, Louis Philippe I, declined to ratify it.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] On 27 April 1848, under the Second Republic (1848–1852), the decree-law written by Victor Schœlcher abolished slavery in the remaining colonies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The state bought the slaves from the *colons* (white colonists; *Békés* in Creole), and then freed them.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] At about the same time, France started colonizing Africa and had gained possession of much of West Africa by 1900.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1905, the French abolished slavery in most of French West Africa.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The French also attempted to abolish Tuareg slavery following the Kaocen Revolt.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In the region of the Sahel, slavery has long persisted.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The abolition wasn't strictly put in place.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Several french territories kept practising slavery until 1904 as was the case in Senegal or 1894 in Soudan.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The abolition was not strictly enforced.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Passed on 10 May 2001, the Taubira law officially acknowledges slavery and the Atlantic slave trade as a crime against humanity.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] 10 May was chosen as the day dedicated to recognition of the crime of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] James Oglethorpe was among the first to articulate the Enlightenment case against slavery, banning it in the Province of Georgia on humanitarian grounds, and arguing against it in Parliament.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Soon after Oglethorpe's death in 1785, Sharp and More united with William Wilberforce and others in forming the Clapham Sect.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The Somersett case in 1772, in which a fugitive slave was freed with the judgement that slavery did not exist under English common law, helped launch the British movement to abolish slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Though anti-slavery sentiments were widespread by the late 18th century, many colonies and emerging nations continued to use slave labor: Dutch, French, British, Spanish, and Portuguese territories in the West Indies, South America, and the Southern United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] After the American Revolution established the United States, many Loyalists who fled the Northern United States immigrated to the British province of Quebec, bringing an English majority population as well as many slaves, leading the province to ban the institution in 1793 (see Slavery in Canada).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1787, the Society for Effecting the Abolition of the Slave Trade was formed in London.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The last known form of enforced servitude of adults (villeinage) had disappeared in England by the beginning of the 17th century.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1569 a court considered the case of Cartwright, who had bought a slave from Russia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The court ruled English law could not recognize slavery, as it was never established officially.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] This ruling was overshadowed by later developments; it was upheld in 1700 by the Lord Chief Justice John Holt when he ruled that a slave became free as soon as he arrived in England.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] During the English Civil Wars of the mid-seventeenth century, sectarian radicals challenged slavery and other threats to personal freedom.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Their ideas influenced many antislavery thinkers in the eighteenth century.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In addition to English colonists importing slaves to the North American colonies, by the 18th century, traders began to import slaves from Africa, India and East Asia (where they were trading) to London and Edinburgh to work as personal servants.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Men who migrated to the North American colonies often took their East Indian slaves or servants with them, as East Indians have been documented in colonial records.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Some of the first freedom suits, court cases in the British Isles to challenge the legality of slavery, took place in Scotland in 1755 and 1769.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Each of the slaves had been baptized in Scotland and challenged the legality of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] They set the precedent of legal procedure in British courts that would later lead to successful outcomes for the plaintiffs.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In these cases, deaths of the plaintiff and defendant, respectively, brought an end before court decisions.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] African slaves were not bought or sold in London but were brought by masters from other areas.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Together with people from other nations, especially non-Christian, Africans were considered foreigners, not able to be English subjects.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] At the time, England had no naturalization procedure.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The African slaves' legal status was unclear until 1772 and Somersett's Case, when the fugitive slave James Somersett forced a decision by the courts.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Somersett had escaped, and his master, Charles Steuart, had him captured and imprisoned on board a ship, intending to ship him to Jamaica to be resold into slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] While in London, Somersett had been baptized; three godparents issued a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] As a result, Lord Mansfield, Chief Justice of the Court of the King's Bench, had to judge whether Somersett's abduction was lawful or not under English common law.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] No legislation had ever been passed to establish slavery in England.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The case received national attention, and five advocates supported the action on behalf of Somersett.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Although the exact legal implications of the judgement are unclear when analysed by lawyers, the judgement was generally taken at the time to have determined that slavery did not exist under English common law and was thus prohibited in England.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The decision did not apply to the British overseas territories; by then, for example, the American colonies had established slavery by positive laws.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Somersett's case became a significant part of the common law of slavery in the English-speaking world and it helped launch the movement to abolish slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] After reading about Somersett's Case, Joseph Knight, an enslaved African who had been purchased by his master John Wedderburn in Jamaica and brought to Scotland, left him.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Married and with a child, he filed a freedom suit, on the grounds that he could not be held as a slave in Great Britain.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* (1778), Wedderburn said that Knight owed him "perpetual servitude".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The Court of Session of Scotland ruled against him, saying that chattel slavery was not recognized under the law of Scotland, and slaves could seek court protection to leave a master or avoid being forcibly removed from Scotland to be returned to slavery in the colonies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] But at the same time, legally mandated, hereditary slavery of Scots persons in Scotland had existed from 1606 and continued until 1799, when colliers and salters were emancipated by an act of the Parliament of Great Britain (39 Geo.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Skilled workers, they were restricted to a place and could be sold with the works.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] 28) was intended to end what the act referred to as "a state of slavery and bondage", but that was ineffective, necessitating the 1799 act.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In the 1776 book *The Wealth of Nations*, Adam Smith argued for the abolition of slavery on economic grounds.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Smith pointed out that slavery incurred security, housing, and food costs that the use of free labor would not, and opined that free workers would be more productive because they would have personal economic incentives to work harder.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The death rate (and thus repurchase cost) of slaves was also high, and people are less productive when not allowed to choose the type of work they prefer, are illiterate, and are forced to live and work in miserable and unhealthy conditions.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The free labor markets and international free trade that Smith preferred would also result in different prices and allocations that Smith believed would be more efficient and productive for consumers.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Prior to the American Revolution, there were few significant initiatives in the American colonies that led to the abolitionist movement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Kent was the lawyer who took on most of the cases of slaves suing their masters for personal illegal enslavement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] He was the first lawyer to successfully establish a slave's freedom.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In addition, Brigadier General Samuel Birch created the *Book of Negroes*, to establish which slaves were free after the war.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1783, an anti-slavery movement began among the British public to end slavery throughout the British Empire.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] After the formation of the Committee for the Abolition of the Slave Trade in 1787, William Wilberforce led the cause of abolition through the parliamentary campaign.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson became the group's most prominent researcher, gathering vast amounts of data on the trade.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] One aspect of abolitionism during this period was the effective use of images such as the famous Josiah Wedgwood "Am I Not A Man and a Brother?" anti-slavery medallion of 1787.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Clarkson described the medallion as "promoting the cause of justice, humanity and freedom".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The 1792 Slave Trade Bill passed the House of Commons mangled and mutilated by the modifications and amendments of Pitt, it lay for years, in the House of Lords.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Biographer William Hague considers the unfinished abolition of the slave trade to be Pitt's greatest failure.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 was passed by the British Parliament on 25 March 1807, making the slave trade illegal throughout the British Empire.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Britain used its influence to coerce other countries to agree to treaties to end their slave trade and allow the Royal Navy to seize their slave ships.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Britain enforced the abolition of the trade because the act made trading slaves within British territories illegal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] However, the act repealed the Amelioration Act 1798 which attempted to improve conditions for slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The end of the slave trade did not end slavery as a whole.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In the 1820s, the abolitionist movement revived to campaign against the institution of slavery itself.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1823 the first Anti-Slavery Society, the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions, was founded.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Many of its members had previously campaigned against the slave trade.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] On 28 August 1833, the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 was passed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It purchased the slaves from their masters and paved the way for the abolition of slavery throughout the British Empire by 1838, after which the first Anti-Slavery Society was wound up.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1839, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society was formed by Joseph Sturge, which attempted to outlaw slavery worldwide and also to pressure the government to help enforce the suppression of the slave trade by declaring slave traders to be pirates.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The world's oldest international human rights organization, it continues today as Anti-Slavery International.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson was the key speaker at the World Anti-Slavery Convention it held in London in 1840.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In the principalities of Wallachia and Moldavia, the government held slavery of the Roma (often referred to as Gypsies) as legal at the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The progressive pro-European and anti-Ottoman movement, which gradually gained power in the two principalities, also worked to abolish that slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Between 1843 and 1855, the principalities emancipated all of the 250,000 enslaved Roma people.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Bartolomé de las Casas was a 16th-century Spanish Dominican priest, the first resident Bishop of Chiapas (Central America, today Mexico).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] As a settler in the New World he witnessed and opposed the poor treatment and virtual slavery of the Native Americans by the Spanish colonists, under the encomienda system.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] He advocated before King Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor on behalf of rights for the natives.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Las Casas for 20 years worked to get African slaves imported to replace natives; African slavery was everywhere and no one talked of ridding the New World of it, though France had abolished slavery in France itself and there was talk in other countries about doing the same.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] However, Las Casas had a late change of heart, and became an advocate for the Africans in the colonies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] His book, *A Short Account of the Destruction of the Indies*, contributed to Spanish passage of colonial legislation known as the New Laws of 1542, which abolished native slavery for the first time in European colonial history.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It ultimately led to the Valladolid debate, the first European debate about the rights of colonized people.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] During the early 19th century, slavery expanded rapidly in Brazil, Cuba, and the United States, while at the same time the new republics of mainland Spanish America became committed to the gradual abolition of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] During the Spanish American wars for independence (1810–1826), slavery was abolished in most of Latin America, though it continued until 1873 in Puerto Rico, 1886 in Cuba, and 1888 in Brazil (where it was abolished by the *Lei Áurea*, the "Golden Law").
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Chile declared freedom of wombs in 1811, followed by the United Provinces of the River Plate in 1813, Colombia and Venezuela in 1821, but without abolishing slavery completely.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] While Chile abolished slavery in 1823, Argentina did so with the signing of the Argentine Constitution of 1853.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Slavery was abolished in Uruguay during the *Guerra Grande*, by both the government of Fructuoso Rivera and the government in exile of Manuel Oribe.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Throughout the growth of slavery in the American South, Nova Scotia became a destination for black refugees leaving Southern Colonies and United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] While many blacks who arrived in Nova Scotia during the American Revolution were free, others were not.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Black slaves also arrived in Nova Scotia as the property of White American Loyalists.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1772, prior to the American Revolution, Britain determined that slavery could not exist in the British Isles followed by the *Knight v.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* decision in Scotland in 1778.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] This decision, in turn, influenced the colony of Nova Scotia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, abolitionist James Drummond MacGregor from Pictou published the first anti-slavery literature in Canada and began purchasing slaves' freedom and chastising his colleagues in the Presbyterian church who owned slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Led by Richard John Uniacke, in 1787, 1789 and again on 11 January 1808, the Nova Scotian legislature refused to legalize slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Two chief justices, Thomas Andrew Lumisden Strange (1790–1796) and Sampson Salter Blowers (1797–1832) were instrumental in freeing slaves from their owners in Nova Scotia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] They were held in high regard in the colony.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] By the end of the War of 1812 and the arrival of the Black Refugees, there were few slaves left in Nova Scotia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 outlawed the slave trade in the British Empire and the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 outlawed slavery altogether.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] With slaves escaping to New York and New England, legislation for gradual emancipation was passed in Upper Canada (1793) and Lower Canada (1803).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In Upper Canada, the Act Against Slavery of 1793 was passed by the Assembly under the auspices of John Graves Simcoe.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It was the first legislation against slavery in the British Empire.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Under its provisions no new slaves could be imported, slaves already in the province would remain enslaved until death, and children born to female slaves would be slaves but must be freed at the age of 25.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The last slaves in Canada gained their freedom when slavery was abolished in the entire British Empire by the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In his book *The Struggle For Equality*, historian James M.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] McPherson defines an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional, and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] He does not include antislavery activists such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party, which called for the gradual ending of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Franklin, a slaveholder for much of his life, became a leading member of the Pennsylvania Society for the Abolition of Slavery, the first recognized organization for abolitionists in the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, Northern states abolished slavery, beginning with the 1777 Constitution of Vermont, followed by Pennsylvania's gradual emancipation act in 1780.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Other states with more of an economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, also passed gradual emancipation laws, and by 1804, all the Northern states had abolished it, although this did not mean that already enslaved people were freed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Some had to work without wages as "indentured servants" for two more decades, although they could no longer be sold.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The 1836–1837 campaign to end free speech in Alton, Illinois, culminated in the 7 November 1837 mob murder of abolitionist newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy, which was covered in newspapers nationwide, causing a rise in membership in abolitionist societies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] By 1840 more than 15,000 people were members of abolitionist societies in the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In the 1850s in the fifteen states constituting the American South, slavery was legally established.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] While it was fading away in the cities as well as in the border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cotton for export, or sugar, tobacco, or hemp.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] According to the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] American abolitionism was based in the North, although there were anti-abolitionist riots in several cities.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In the South abolitionism was illegal, and abolitionist publications, like The Liberator, could not be sent to Southern post offices.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Amos Dresser, a white alumnus of Lane Theological Seminary, was publicly whipped in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing abolitionist publications.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In addition, laws were passed to further repress slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] These laws included anti-literacy laws and anti-gathering laws.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The anti-gathering laws were applied to religious gatherings of free blacks and slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] These laws, passed around the 1820–1850 period, were blamed in the South on Northern abolitionists.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] As one slaveowner wrote, "I can tell you.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Abolitionism in the United States became a popular expression of moralism, operating in tandem with other social reform efforts, such as the temperance movement, and much more problematically, the women's suffrage movement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison (founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society) and writers Wendell Phillips, John Greenleaf Whittier, and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners of using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The Republican Party wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because it believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] White Southern leaders said that the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the territories made them second-class citizens and, as the *Dred Scott* decision held, infringed slaveholders' property rights.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and the labor of enslaved people decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the Confederacy's firing on Fort Sumter, a Union fort in South Carolina.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] When Lincoln called for troops to suppress the rebellion, four more slave states seceded.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, four slave states, known as the border states (Maryland, Missouri, Delaware, and Kentucky), chose to remain in the Union.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] On 16 April 1862, Abraham Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, abolishing slavery in Washington D.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of escaped slaves from the South rushing to Union lines.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, called contrabands, so that they would not be returned to their masters in the Confederacy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] On 1 January 1863, Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which was an executive order of the U.S. government that changed the legal status of 3 million slaves in the Confederacy from "slave" to "henceforward ... free".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Though slaves were legally freed by the Proclamation, they became actually free by escaping to federal lines, or by advances of federal troops.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Even before the Emancipation Proclamation, many former slaves served the federal army as teamsters, cooks, laundresses, and laborers, as well as scouts, spies, and guides.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Plantation owners sometimes moved the Black people they claimed to own as far as possible out of reach of the Union army.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] By "Juneteenth" (19 June 1865, in Texas), the Union Army controlled all of the Confederacy and liberated all its slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The owners were never compensated; nor were freed slaves compensated by former owners.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The border states were exempt from the Emancipation Proclamation, but they too (except Delaware) began their own emancipation programs.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] As the war dragged on, both the federal government and Union states continued to take measures against slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In June 1864, the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, which required free states to aid in returning escaped slaves to slave states, was repealed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The state of Maryland abolished slavery on 13 October 1864.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Missouri abolished slavery on 11 January 1865.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] West Virginia, which had been admitted to the Union in 1863 as a slave state, but on the condition of gradual emancipation, fully abolished slavery on 3 February 1865.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Constitution took effect in December 1865, seven months after the end of the war, and finally ended slavery for non-criminals throughout the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It also abolished slavery among the Indian tribes, including the Alaska tribes that became part of the U.S. in 1867.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Brazil and Cuba abolished slavery in the 1880s, with Cuba ending it in 1886 and Brazil in 1888.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] While actors like Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda in Cuba and Adelina Charuteira in Brazil worked to end slavery, it was enslaved people themselves who worked daily to chip away at enslavers' local authority.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] These practices are regionally specific based on the legal customs of the region that enslaved people knew well from centuries of interactions with Iberian slave laws.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] A key avenue for these legal arguments was the prominence of "lo extrajudicial", a field of legal interactions adjacent to a lawsuit explained by historian Bianca Premo as consisting of out-of-court settlements, public revelations, and face-to-face encounters.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The suffering of women in slavery was a common trope consistently used in abolitionists' rhetoric on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] This was especially true as it relates to the image of suffering mothers and their children.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Towards the end of the nineteenth century as slavery was coming to an end throughout the Atlantic world, images appearing in abolitionist publications routinely included images of families being torn apart and pregnant women being forced to do hard labor.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] As countries imposed "free womb laws" to soften the image of slavery and bring about gradual emancipation, for many it raised the question of the justice of women being used to carry out emancipation without benefiting from it themselves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Speeches given on the topic at the time focused on mothers and compared them to "all other mothers", using motherhood to level the subjects and objects of their speech.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Women were also often on the forefront of the abolition movement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Authors such as Harriet Beecher Stowe (United States) and Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda (Brazil) used their novels to call into question the humanity of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Women such as the Grimké Sisters, Abigail Adams, Elizabeth Cady Stanton and others used their connections to political movements to advocate for the abolition of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women such as Phillis Wheatley and Harriet Tubman took matters into their own hands by challenging the institution of slavery through their writing and their actions.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women like Adelina Charuteira used their mobility as street vendors and as much access as they had to literacy to spread information about abolition between freedom-seeking people and local abolitionist networks.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] White and black opponents of slavery, who played a considerable role in the movement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] This list includes some escaped slaves, who were traditionally called abolitionists.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The first international attempt to address the abolition of slavery was the World Anti-Slavery Convention, organised by the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society at Exeter Hall in London, on 12–23 June 1840.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] This was however an attempt made by NGOs, not by state and governments.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In the late 19th century, the issue was addressed on an international level by states and governments.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The Brussels Anti-Slavery Conference 1889–90 addressed slavery on a semi-global level via the representatives of the colonial powers.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] It had concluded with the Brussels Conference Act of 1890.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The 1890 Act was revised by the Convention of Saint-Germain-en-Laye 1919.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] During the 20th century the issue of slavery was addressed by the League of Nations, which founded commissions to investigate and eradicate the institution of slavery and slave trade worldwide.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The Temporary Slavery Commission (TSC), which was founded in 1924, conducted a global investigation and filed a report, and a convention was drawn up to hasten the total abolition of slavery and the slave trade.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The 1926 Slavery Convention, which was founded upon the investigation of the TSC of the League of Nations, was a turning point in banning global slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In 1932, the League formed the Committee of Experts on Slavery (CES) to review the result and enforcement of the 1926 Slavery Convention, which resulted in a new international investigation under the first permanent slavery committee, the Advisory Committee of Experts on Slavery (ACE).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The ACE conducted a major international investigation on slavery and slave trade, inspecting all the colonial empires and the territories under their control between 1934 and 1939.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted in 1948 by the UN General Assembly, explicitly banned slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] After World War II, chattel slavery was formally abolished by law in almost the entire world, with the exception of the Arabian Peninsula and some parts of Africa.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Chattel slavery was still legal in Saudi Arabia, in Yemen, in the Trucial States and in Oman, and slaves were supplied to the Arabian Peninsula via the Red Sea slave trade.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The United Nations 1956 Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery was convened to outlaw and ban slavery worldwide, including child slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In November 1962, Faisal of Saudi Arabia finally prohibited the owning of slaves in Saudi Arabia, followed by the abolition of slavery in Yemen in 1962, slavery in Dubai 1963 and slavery in Oman in 1970.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In December 1966, the UN General Assembly adopted the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which was developed from the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of this international treaty bans slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The treaty came into force in March 1976 after it had been ratified by 35 nations.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] As of November 2003, 104 nations had ratified the treaty.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] However, illegal forced labor involves millions of people in the 21st century, 43% for sexual exploitation and 32% for economic exploitation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Currently, the Anti-trafficking Coordination Team Initiative (ACT Team Initiative), a coordinated effort between the U.S.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Departments of Justice, Homeland Security, and Labor, addresses human trafficking.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] The International Labour Organization estimates that there are 20.9 million victims of human trafficking globally, including 5.5 million children, of which 55% are women and girls.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] In societies with large proportions of the population working in conditions of slavery or serfdom, stroke-of-the-pen laws declaring abolition can have thorough-going social, economic and political consequences.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p01] Issues of compensation/redemption, land-redistribution and citizenship can prove intractable.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] People in modern times have commemorated abolitionist movements and the abolition of slavery in different ways around the world.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] The United Nations General Assembly declared 2004 the International Year to Commemorate the Struggle against Slavery and its Abolition.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] This proclamation marked the bicentenary of the proclamation of the first modern slavery-free state, Haiti.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Numerous exhibitions, events and research programmes became associated with the initiative.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] 2007 witnessed major exhibitions in British museums and galleries to mark the anniversary of the 1807 abolition act – 1807 Commemorated 2008 marked the 201st anniversary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade in the British Empire.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] It also marked the 175th anniversary of the abolition of slavery in the British Empire.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] The Faculty of Law at the University of Ottawa held a major international conference entitled, "Routes to Freedom: Reflections on the Bicentenary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade", from 14 to 16 March 2008.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Abolitionist constitutionalism is a line of thinking which invokes the historical view of the Constitution of the United States as an abolitionist document.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] It calls for an appeal to constitutionalism and progressive constitutionalism.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] This vision is interdisciplinary and finds its roots in the anti-slavery movement in the United States of America and is largely based on the tenet that current state institutions, particularly the carceral system, is rooted in the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Some constitutional abolitionists critique the claim that the Constitution was pro-slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionist constitutionalism calls for the idea of dignity and the use of jurisprudence to address social inequalities.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Constitution was pro-slavery, the Reconstruction Amendments can be seen as a compromise for freedom, without allowing for the full abolition.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Criminal punishment was a major way that Southern states maintained the exploitation of black labor and effectively nullified the Reconstruction Amendments.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] This was done namely through Black Codes, harsh vagrancy laws, apprenticeship laws and extreme punishment for black people.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] The Reconstruction Amendments in their aim to promote citizenship and emancipation are believed by these thinkers to still be guiding principles in the fight for freedom and abolition.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] There are suggestions that a broad reading of the Thirteenth Amendment can convey an abolitionist vision of the freedom advocated for by black people in the public sphere beyond emancipation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Section one of the Fourteenth Amendment was used by many abolitionist lawyers and activists throughout the North to advance the case against slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Proponents of abolitionist constitutionalism believe the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Amendments can be used today to extend the abolitionist logics to the various current barriers to injustices that are faced by marginalized peoples.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Just like abolitionism more generally, abolitionist constitutionalism seeks to provide a vision which will lead to the abolition of many different neoliberal state institutions, such as the prison industrial complex, the wage system, and policing.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] This is tied to a belief that white supremacy is woven into the fabric of legal state institutions.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionists are often marginalized.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] There is a belief that constitutionalism as a main tenet of radical abolitionism can change and appeal to the popular opinion more.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Historically, slavery abolitionists have had to use the public meaning of Constitutional terms in order in their fight against slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Constitutional abolitionists are generally in favour of incremental changes that follow the principles of the Reconstructive Amendments.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Some argue that the narrative and scholarly literature around Reconstruction Amendments is not coherent regarding their original aims.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] On 10 December 1948, the General Assembly of the United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Although outlawed in most countries, slavery is nonetheless practised secretly in many parts of the world.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Enslavement still takes place in the United States, Europe, and Latin America, as well as parts of Africa, the Middle East, and South Asia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Modern slavery keeps around 50 million people from exercising their freedom.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] In Mauritania alone, estimates are that up to 600,000 men, women and children, or 20% of the population, are enslaved.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Modern-day abolitionists have emerged over the last several years, as awareness of slavery around the world has grown, with groups such as Anti-Slavery International, the American Anti-Slavery Group, International Justice Mission, and Free the Slaves working to rid the world of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] In the United States, The Action Group to End Human Trafficking and Modern-Day Slavery is a coalition of NGOs, foundations and corporations working to develop a policy agenda for abolishing slavery and human trafficking.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Since 1997, the United States Department of Justice has, through work with the Coalition of Immokalee Workers, prosecuted six individuals in Florida on charges of slavery in the agricultural industry.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] These prosecutions have led to freedom for over 1000 enslaved workers in the tomato and orange fields of South Florida.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] This is only one example of the contemporary fight against slavery worldwide.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Slavery exists most widely in agricultural labor, apparel and sex industries, and service jobs in some regions.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] In 2000, the United States passed the Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act (TVPA) "to combat trafficking in persons, especially into the sex trade, slavery, and involuntary servitude".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] The 13th amendment abolished slavery in the United States "except as a punishment for crime whereof the party shall have been duly convicted".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] In 2018, Colorado became the first state to remove similar language in its state constitution by a legislatively referred ballot referendum.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abolitionism-p02] Other states have followed suit, but implementation has relied on court rulings.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The **African Methodist Episcopal Church**, usually called the **AME Church** or **AME**, is a Methodist denomination based in the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It adheres to Wesleyan–Arminian theology and has a connexional polity.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It cooperates with other Methodist bodies through the World Methodist Council and Wesleyan Holiness Connection.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Though historically a black church and the first independent Protestant denomination to be founded by Black people, the African Methodist Episcopal Church welcomes and has members of all ethnicities.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME Church was founded by Richard Allen (1760–1831) in 1787 when he called together five African American congregations of the previously established Methodist Episcopal Church with the hope of escaping the discrimination that was commonplace in society, including some churches.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It was among the first denominations in the United States to be founded for this reason (rather than for theological distinctions).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The denomination then expanded west and through the South, particularly after the American Civil War (1861–1865).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME Church currently has 20 districts, each with its own bishop: 13 are based in the United States, mostly in the South, while seven are based in Africa.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The global membership of the AME is around 2.5 million members, and it remains one of the largest Methodist denominations in the world.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] taken to the Americas) as a response to being officially discriminated against by white congregants in the Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The church was not founded in Africa, nor is it exclusively for people of African descent.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It is open and welcoming to people of all ethnic groups, origins, nationalities, and colors, although its congregations are predominantly made up of black Americans.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] George's Methodist Church left the congregation when faced with racial discrimination, but continued with the Methodist doctrine and the order of worship.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The denomination leaders are bishops of the church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME Church worked out of the Free African Society (FAS), which Richard Allen, Absalom Jones, and other free blacks established in Philadelphia in 1787.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] George's Methodist Episcopal Church because of discrimination.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] These members erected a site of worship to escape the "unkind treatment of their white brethren, who considered them a nuisance in the house of worship." They were told if they did not give up this space, they would be publicly expelled from the church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] They resigned, an action that was supported by some white benefactors, including one who ordained Absalom Jones as their pastor.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Although Allen and Jones were both accepted as preachers, they were limited to black congregations.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In addition, the blacks were made to sit in a separate gallery built in the church when their portion of the congregation increased.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] George's made plans to transform their mutual aid society into an African congregation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Although the group was originally non-denominational, eventually members wanted to affiliate with existing denominations.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Allen led a small group who resolved to remain Methodist.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] They formed the Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church in 1793.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In general, they adopted the doctrines and form of government of the Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In 1794 Bethel AME was dedicated with Allen as pastor.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] To establish Bethel's independence, Allen successfully sued in the Pennsylvania courts in 1807 and 1815 for the right of his congregation to exist as an institution independent of white Methodist congregations.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Because black Methodists in other middle Atlantic communities also encountered racism and desired religious autonomy, Allen called them to meet in Philadelphia in 1816 to form a new Wesleyan denomination.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Sixteen representatives, from Bethel African Church in Philadelphia and African churches in Baltimore, MD, Wilmington, DE, Attleboro, PA, and Salem, NJ, met to form a church organization or connection under the title of the "African Methodist Episcopal Church".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It began with eight clergy and five churches, and by 1846 had grown to 176 clergy, 296 churches, and 17,375 members.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Safe villages, like the village of Lima, Pennsylvania, were set up with nearby AME churches and were sometimes involved in the Underground Railroad.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The 20,000 members in 1856 were located primarily in the North.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] AME national membership (including probationers and preachers) jumped from 70,000 in 1866 to 207,000 in 1876.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The church also expanded internationally during this period.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Other Bermudians, such as First Sergeant Robert John Simmons of the 54th Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry Regiment, fought to end slavery in the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Among the numerous residents of the American South with ties to Bermuda was Denmark Vesey, who was brought to South Carolina from Bermuda as a slave before purchasing his freedom.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Vesey was a founder of Mother Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church before his execution after conviction in a show trial resulting from white hysteria over an alleged conspiracy for a slave revolt in 1822.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The majority of the population of Bermuda during the first century of settlement was European, with free and enslaved blacks primarily from the Spanish West Indies and Native Americans, primarily from New England (anyone not entirely of European ancestry was counted as *coloured*).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] As any child of a coloured and a white parent was counted as coloured, the ratio of the white to coloured population shifted during the course of the 18th century (4,850 whites and 3,514 coloured in 1721; but 4,755 whites and 5,425 coloured in 1811).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The Church of England was the established church, and was the only church originally permitted to operate in Bermuda.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Presbyterians were permitted to have a separate church and to conduct their own services during the 18th century.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The Wesleyan Methodists sought to include enslaved blacks and a law was passed by the Parliament of Bermuda in 1800 barring any but Church of England and Presbyterian ministers from preaching.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The Methodist Reverend John Stephenson was incarcerated in December, 1800, for six months for preaching to slaves.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The law and attitudes changed during the course of the following century, but any church organised by blacks and organising blacks would not be welcomed by the white dominated Government.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Stephenson was followed in 1808 by the Reverend Joshua Marsden.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] There were 136 members of the Society when Marsden left Bermuda in 1812.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Lloyd's negative comments on the *dissenters* was in reference to the Wesleyan Methodists.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The degree of education of coloured Bermudians would be noted by later visitors, also.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The foundation stone of a Wesleyan Methodist Chapel was laid in St.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] George's Town on the 8 June 1840, the local Society (by then numbering 37 class leaders, 489 members, and 20 other communicants) having previously occupied a small, increasingly decrepit building that had been damaged beyond use in a storm in 1839.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME First District website records that in the autumn of 1869, *three farsighted Christian men—Benjamin Burchall of St.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Jennings of Devonshire and Charles Roach Ratteray of Somerset—set in motion the wheels that brought African Methodism to* Bermuda.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] As the Imperial Government had ruled that the AME Church could operate in the United Kingdom, the first AME church in Bermuda was erected in 1885 in Hamilton Parish, on the shore of Harrington Sound, and titled St.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] John African Methodist Episcopal Church (the congregation had begun previously as part of the British Methodist Episcopal Church of Canada).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Although the Church of England (since 1978, titled the Anglican Church of Bermuda) remains the largest denomination in Bermuda (15.8%), the AME quickly flourished (accounting for 8.6% of the population today), overtaking the Wesleyan Methodists (2.7% today).
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The rise of the Wesleyan-Holiness movement in Methodism influenced the African Methodist Episcopal Church, with Jarena Lee and Amanda Smith preaching the doctrine of entire sanctification throughout pulpits of the connexion.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In the 19th century, the AME Church of Ohio collaborated with the Methodist Episcopal Church, a predominantly white denomination, in sponsoring the second independent historically black college (HBCU), Wilberforce University in Ohio.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] By 1880, AME operated over 2,000 schools, chiefly in the South, with 155,000 students.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] For school houses they used church buildings; the ministers and their wives were the teachers; the congregations raised the money to keep schools operating at a time the segregated public schools were starved of funds.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] After the America Civil War, Bishop Henry McNeal Turner (1834–1915) was a major leader of the AME and played a role in Republican Party politics.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In 1863 during the American Civil War, Turner was appointed as the first black chaplain in the United States Colored Troops.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Afterward, he was appointed to the Freedmen's Bureau in Georgia.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] He settled in Macon, Georgia, and was elected to the state legislature in 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] He planted many AME churches in Georgia after the war.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In 1880 he was elected as the first southern bishop of the AME Church after a fierce battle within the denomination.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Angered by the Democrats' regaining power and instituting Jim Crow laws in the late nineteenth century South, Turner was the leader of black nationalism and proposed emigration of blacks to Africa.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The African Methodist Episcopal Church has a unique history as it is the first major religious denomination in the western world that developed because of race rather than theological differences.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It was the first African-American denomination organized and incorporated in the United States.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The church was born in protest against racial discrimination and slavery.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Among Wilberforce University's early founders was Salmon P.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Chase, then-governor of Ohio and the future Secretary of Treasury under President Abraham Lincoln.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Other members of the FAS wanted to affiliate with the Episcopal Church and followed Absalom Jones in doing that.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In 1792, they founded the African Episcopal Church of St.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Thomas, the first Episcopal church in the United States with a founding black congregation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In 1804, Jones was ordained as the first black priest in the Episcopal Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] While the AME is doctrinally Methodist, clergy, scholars, and lay persons have written works that demonstrate the distinctive racial theology and *praxis* that have come to define this Wesleyan body.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] DuBois said AME was "the greatest Negro organization in the world".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In an address to the 1893 World's Parliament of Religions, Bishop Benjamin W.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Arnett reminded the audience of blacks' influence in the formation of Christianity.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Tanner wrote in 1895 in *The Color of Solomon – What?* that biblical scholars wrongly portrayed the son of David as a white man.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] In the post-civil rights era, theologians James Cone, Cecil W.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Cone, and Jacqueline Grant, who came from the AME tradition, criticized Euro-centric Christianity and African-American churches for their shortcomings in resolving the plight of those oppressed by racism, sexism, and economic disadvantage.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The World Council of Churches estimates the membership of the AME Church at around 2,510,000; 3,817 pastors, 21 bishops and 7,000 congregations.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The General Conference is the supreme body of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It is composed of the bishops, as *ex officio* presidents, according to the rank of election, and an equal number of ministerial and lay delegates, elected by each of the annual conferences and the lay electoral colleges of the annual conferences.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Other *ex officio* members are: the general officers, college presidents, deans of theological seminaries; and chaplains in the regular United States Armed Forces.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The General Conference meets every four years, but may have extra sessions in certain emergencies.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] At the General Conference of the AME Church, notable and renowned speakers have been invited to address the clergy and laity of the congregation.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Such as in 2008, the church invited then Senator Barack H.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] Obama, and in 2012, the church invited then First Lady of the United States Michelle Obama.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The Council of Bishops is the executive branch of the church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It has the general oversight of the church during the interim between general conferences.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME Council of Bishops shall meet annually at such time and place as the majority of the council shall determine and also at such other times as may be deemed necessary in the discharging its responsibility as the executive branch of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] This council shall hold at least two public sessions at each annual meeting.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] At the first, complaints and petitions against a bishop shall be heard, at the second, the decisions of the council shall be made public.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The Board of Incorporators, also known as the General Board of Trustees, has the supervision, in trust, of all connectional property of the church and is vested with authority to act in behalf of the AME Church wherever necessary.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The Judicial Council is the highest judicatory body of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] It is an appellate court, elected by the General Conference and is amenable to it.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The African Methodist Episcopal Church cooperates with other Methodist bodies through the World Methodist Council and Wesleyan Holiness Connection.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME motto, "God Our Father, Christ Our Redeemer, Holy Spirit Our Comforter, Humankind Our Family", reflects the basic beliefs of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The basic foundations of the beliefs of the church can be summarized in the Apostles' Creed, and the 25 Articles of Religion, held in common with other Methodist denominations.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The church also observes the official bylaws of the AME Church.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The "Doctrine and Discipline of the African Methodist Episcopal Church" is revised at every AME General Conference and published every four years.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME Church also follows the rule that a minister of the denomination must retire at age 75, with bishops, more specifically, being required to retire upon the general conference nearest their 75th birthday.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME Church is active regarding issues of social justice and has invested time in reforming the criminal justice system.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME Church also opposes "elective abortion".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] On women's issues, the AME has supported gender equality and, in 2000, first elected a woman to become bishop.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] While always being open to people of all racial backgrounds, the AME has advocated for the civil and human rights of ethnic minorities, such as African Americans, through social improvement, religious autonomy, and political engagement.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The African Methodist Episcopal Church unanimously voted to forbid ministers from blessing same-sex unions in July 2004.
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The church leaders stated that homosexual activity "clearly contradicts [their] understanding of Scripture" and that the call of the African Methodist Episcopal Church "is to hear the voice of God in our Scriptures".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The AME Church voted to take "a stand against climate change".
[src:african-methodist-episcopal-church/african-methodist-episcopal-church] The African Methodist Episcopal Church has been one of the forerunners of education within the African-American community.
